Step by Step CHIRPS

2022-10-26

CHIRPS data download and basic manipulation reference guide

Elaborated by : Juan Miguel Vquez, Jorge Mass, Daniel Knopp

GitHub repository link

The following guide will include reference for:

  • Processing previously downloaded precipitation data from CHIRPS, within RStudio
  • Spatial data analysis
  • Ideas for graphs for data representation
  • Processed information download

Plotting CHIRPS data for a river basin

1. Install the required packages for all these step by step guides

    #install.packages("terra")
    #install.packages("rasterVis")
    #install.packages("lubridate")
    #install.packages("ggplot2")
    #install.packages("reshape2")
    #install.packages("RColorBrewer")
    #install.packages("dygraphs")

Terra is used for raster and vector spatial data analysis. More info on Terra

2. Load the packages in the Rstudio session

    library(rasterVis)

    library(lubridate)

3. Create the path for the Chirps dataset

This is the directory in the PC where Chirps is stored, change it to your computers directory, accordingly. If you are using .tiff files:

    path_tiff <- "D:/Assist/IWRM/Talleres/CHIRPS/CHIRPS"

Or if you are using an netcdf file:

  path_nc <-"D:/Assist/IWRM/Talleres/chirps-v2.0.monthly.nc"

4. Read the files

If using .tiff files, is needed to read the names of these files and create a list() from them:

    Chirps_files <- list.files(path_tiff,
                           pattern = NULL,
                           all.files = FALSE,
                           full.names = TRUE)
head(Chirps_files)
## [1] "D:/Assist/IWRM/Talleres/CHIRPS/CHIRPS/chirps-v2.0.1981.01.tif"
## [2] "D:/Assist/IWRM/Talleres/CHIRPS/CHIRPS/chirps-v2.0.1981.02.tif"
## [3] "D:/Assist/IWRM/Talleres/CHIRPS/CHIRPS/chirps-v2.0.1981.03.tif"
## [4] "D:/Assist/IWRM/Talleres/CHIRPS/CHIRPS/chirps-v2.0.1981.04.tif"
## [5] "D:/Assist/IWRM/Talleres/CHIRPS/CHIRPS/chirps-v2.0.1981.05.tif"
## [6] "D:/Assist/IWRM/Talleres/CHIRPS/CHIRPS/chirps-v2.0.1981.06.tif"

When using netcdf files, the only requirement is to read it (info on NC files):

    chirps<-rast(path_nc)

5. Create a stack

This step would be required for .tiff files only, more information on stacks can be found here.

    chirps <- rast(Chirps_files)
chirps
## class       : SpatRaster 
## dimensions  : 2000, 7200, 501  (nrow, ncol, nlyr)
## resolution  : 0.05, 0.05  (x, y)
## extent      : -180, 180, -50, 50  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## coord. ref. : lon/lat WGS 84 (EPSG:4326) 
## sources     : chirps-v2.0.1981.01.tif  
##               chirps-v2.0.1981.02.tif  
##               chirps-v2.0.1981.03.tif  
##               ... and 498 more source(s)
## names       : chirp~81.01, chirp~81.02, chirp~81.03, chirp~81.04, chirp~81.05, chirp~81.06, ...

A raster stack has 3 dimensions (X, Y, Time), each of the rasters have the monthly average precipitation and each of the pixels within these rasters contains the precipitation value on the location for that month. For plotting the data, since the stack has 3 dimensions, using variablename\[\[\]] will provide access to a specific time:

    plot(chirps[[1]])

### 6. Loading the Area of Interest Given that CHIRPS is a global product, it is recommended to crop the area to the study region. In order to do this, a Shapefile is used as a cookie cutter to extract only the data within the area of interest (AOI). To load a shapefile the vect() function from the terra package is used (be aware of only using the .shp file and not the others ending on .shx or any other extension):

    Aguan_basin_path <- "D:/IWRM/GIS/Cuencas/Honduras/Aguan/Aguan_basin.shp"
    Aguan_basin <- vect(Aguan_basin_path)
    plot(Aguan_basin)

Adjusting the reference system

If the crs of the stack and the SHP do not match, the shapefile can be reprojected to the coordinates system of the raster. This can be checked with:

7. Cut to the AOI

For this, two functions are needed. The first one is the crop() function (more info here):

    chirps_crop <- crop(chirps, Aguan_basin, snap = 'out')
chirps_crop
## class       : SpatRaster 
## dimensions  : 24, 43, 501  (nrow, ncol, nlyr)
## resolution  : 0.05, 0.05  (x, y)
## extent      : -87.45, -85.3, 14.8, 16  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## coord. ref. : lon/lat WGS 84 (EPSG:4326) 
## source      : memory 
## names       : chirp~81.01, chirp~81.02, chirp~81.03, chirp~81.04, chirp~81.05, chirp~81.06, ... 
## min values  :  -9999.0000,  -9999.0000,   -9999.000, -9999.00000,  -9999.0000,  -9999.0000, ... 
## max values  :    215.6551,    520.1174,     141.909,    91.17754,    182.3561,    342.2977, ...

Plot the data:

plot(chirps_crop[[1]])
lines(Aguan_basin)

The second function is mask(), this one eliminates any NAs resulting from the crop. (Always crop first and mask second, otherwise you will try to mask the whole extend of the datasheet and it takes a lot of processing and thus time)

    chirps_aguan <- mask(chirps_crop, Aguan_basin)
    plot(chirps_aguan[[1]])
    lines(Aguan_basin)

8. Get a monthly average plot and monthly string

With tapp(), an average is extracted from the cropped raster stack, for the index time period. In order to get the monthly average an index=1:12 is used and this way the names of the months to the raster layer can be assigned:

    monthly_chirps<-tapp(chirps_aguan, index = 1:12, fun = mean)
    names(monthly_chirps)<-c('Jan','Feb','Mar','Apr','May','Jun','Jul','Aug','Sep','Oct','Nov','Dec')
monthly_chirps

## resolution  : 0.05, 0.05  (x, y)

## max values  : 208.53408, 162.18019, 122.39014, 72.27700, 150.87371, 204.56672, ...

Next, using a levelplot fthe monthly averages are ploted for the AOI (see more info here)

levelplot(monthly_chirps,layout=c(4,3),contour=T,col.regions=hcl.colors(100))

Extract mean precipitation

This takes the already cropped and masked stack, for extracting the values inside a specific shapefile. It is done with the extract() function and fun is the treatment applied to the extraction, it can be the mean but also the min, max, sum or even a created function (more on functions, here):

    extracted_values <- extract(chirps_aguan,Aguan_basin, fun = "mean")
    extracted_values[1:10]
##   ID chirps.v2.0.1981.01 chirps.v2.0.1981.02 chirps.v2.0.1981.03
## 1  1            36.20252            112.5985            38.79055
##   chirps.v2.0.1981.04 chirps.v2.0.1981.05 chirps.v2.0.1981.06
## 1            24.59033            117.9953            215.5943
##   chirps.v2.0.1981.07 chirps.v2.0.1981.08 chirps.v2.0.1981.09
## 1            134.6842            175.4714            176.8396

The list is transformed into a dataframe and then transposed, this way it is set into a date/value format, the first line is avoided, as it corresponds to the rows name:

extracted_values <- as.numeric(extracted_values[2:502])
values <- as.data.frame(extracted_values)
head(values)
##   extracted_values
## 1         36.20252
## 2        112.59848
## 3         38.79055
## 4         24.59033
## 5        117.99532
## 6        215.59430

For the .tiff files, vectors are created for each month in the time series. The files name is used for this (using this as an example chirps-v2.0.2020.09.tif) the characters 13-19 are selected, which correspond to 2020.09 from the files name and that is used to create a vector (the code below does that for all months):

    Dates <- substr(basename(Chirps_files), 13, 19)
    head(Dates)
## [1] "1981.01" "1981.02" "1981.03" "1981.04" "1981.05" "1981.06"

For the .netCDF files, here is how to create the vectors for each month on the time series:

    Dates_nc <- seq(mdy("01-01-81"),mdy("09-01-22"),by="months")
    head(Dates_nc)
## [1] "1981-01-01" "1981-02-01" "1981-03-01" "1981-04-01" "1981-05-01"
## [6] "1981-06-01"

The next step is to attach the dates and the extracted_values in a table, for the .tiff files:

    Precipitation_Aguan <- cbind(Dates, values)
    head(Precipitation_Aguan) 
##     Dates extracted_values
## 1 1981.01         36.20252
## 2 1981.02        112.59848
## 3 1981.03         38.79055
## 4 1981.04         24.59033
## 5 1981.05        117.99532
## 6 1981.06        215.59430

For the .netCDF files:

    Precipitation_Aguan <- data.frame(Dates_nc, values)
    head(Precipitation_Aguan)
##     Dates_nc extracted_values
## 1 1981-01-01         36.20252
## 2 1981-02-01        112.59848
## 3 1981-03-01         38.79055
## 4 1981-04-01         24.59033
## 5 1981-05-01        117.99532
## 6 1981-06-01        215.59430

Artificial stations using CHIRPS

By creating a points layer, values can be extracted for specific locations within the basin. #### 1. Create a table Initially, a table of X (lon) and Y (lat) coordinates is created and then with the function vect() a point vector is created. Make sure the coordinate system of reference is also on WGS84.

xy <- cbind(c(-87.000,-86.500,-86.000),c(15.202,15.403,15.800))
p <- vect(xy, crs="+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84")
plot(Aguan_basin)
points(p)

2. Extract several points from a raster stack

Since the coordinates of the points of interest have been set, the next steps is to extract the values for the point layer. Note: Extract can also use other functions (max,min,sum)

extracted_values_points <- extract(chirps_aguan, p, fun = "mean")

Crop the index row, so that the first one from the data frame is eliminated. Following the same procedure:

values_points <- (as.data.frame(extracted_values_points[2:481]))
Dates <- substr(basename(Chirps_files), 13, 19)
values_points[,10]
## [1] 136.3382 233.0837 236.4804

3: Creating a data frame for the extracted values

Now, once again it is required to transpose the rows with the columns, in order to create a table and then bind the rows with the Dates vector:

Precipitation_Aguan<-t(rbind(Dates,values_points))
## Warning in rbind(deparse.level, ...): number of columns of result, 480, is not a
## multiple of vector length 501 of arg 1
Precipitation_Aguan<-as.data.frame(Precipitation_Aguan)
head(Precipitation_Aguan)

5. Saving it as a CSV file

For this, write.csv() is used. Note: Add the file extension of the format to the file name

write.csv(Precipitation_Aguan,"D:/Assist/IWRM/Talleres/Cuenca_Aguan.csv")

Plotting the data frame

1. Add a path to the CSV file:

aguan <- "D:/Assist/IWRM/Talleres/Cuenca_Aguan.csv"

2. Open the CSV file:

aguan_csv <- read.csv(aguan)

3. Additional pre-processing of the data

Normally, 90% of the time we have to spend a little longer getting the information on the correct format for visualization. On this case, if plotting the aguan_csv as it is, there is an extra column which is not needed. This could either be ignored or a new data frame excluding that column can be created.

df <- data.frame(aguan_csv$date, aguan_csv$lower, aguan_csv$middle, aguan_csv$upper)

The headers can also be renamed with colnames():

colnames(df) <- c("date", "lower" , "middle" , "upper")

4.a Plot the information

With the data frame ready, it is possible to plot it:

plot(df$date, df$lower, type="l")
lines(df$date, df$middle, type="l", col="red")

Basic plot functions in R can be used, but there are packages that use CSS or Javascript with additional styling and interaction. For example, ggplot2 and dygraph which can create interactives plots.

4.b Other simple plotting options

The date is processed:

d <- melt(df, id.vars="date")

Then the ggplot() function is used, the first variable is the data frame and defining geom_line tells ggplot to graph lines, points could also be used and so on. With stat_smooth a tendency for lines is added to each group and the final part is adding a title to the graph and the axis:

ggplot(d, aes(date, value, col = variable))+
geom_line(size=2)+
stat_smooth()+
ggtitle("Precipitation")+
xlab("date")+
ylab("values")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

With the RColorBrewer package is possible to check the color palette and add it as well:

Plots can be separated by column variables:

    ggplot(d, aes(date,value))+
    geom_line()+
    facet_wrap(~variable)

## Plotting with dygraphs The previous packages allow also to style plots for spatial analysis. The next package is dygraphs, which has more options for creating interactive plots. A simple plot with this package, is one where the function already recognize all the columns of the data frame:

dygraph(df)

Then the following functions below are for improving and highlighting more information from the plot: Note: for each extra add-on for the plot, in order to avoid repetition and extending the code, pipes are used. For ggplot are + and for dygraph %>%

A range selector can be added, for some interactivity:

dygraph(df) %>% dyRangeSelector()

And the final plot would include many other characteristics, as needed:

dygraph(df, main = "Aguan") %>% dyRangeSelector() %>%
  dySeries("lower", label = "Lower", color ="green") %>%
  dySeries("middle", label = "Middle", color = "black") %>%
  dySeries("upper", label = "Upper", color = "red") %>%
  dyOptions(stackedGraph = TRUE) %>%
  dyRangeSelector(height = 20) %>%
  dyHighlight(highlightSeriesOpts = list(strokeWidth = 3)) %>%
  dyAxis("y", label = "Descarga") %>%
  dyAxis("x", label ="Fecha")

In order to save the graph and keep the interactivity, there is an option at the Plots browser: Click on the Export button and then select the option Save as Web Page.
